Advanced Search Simple Search
To search for a property, enter the address into the search field and press the "Search" button.
Unit numbers must be separated by a forward slash [ / ]. For example: "10/2 Smith Street Epping NSW 2121".
If you are having trouble finding a property, try the Advanced Search which can search partial street and suburb names and street number ranges.

    To search for a property, enter the parcel description into the search field and press the "Search" button. Lot and plan is separated by a forward slash [ / ]. For example: "269/RP9348 Newstead QLD" Search
    To search for a property, enter a company name into the search field and press the "Search" button. For example: "Smart Creations Pty Ltd"
    Tick to return only properties that the company currently owns.
    Search

    Type a full or partial last name into the field. If you do not know the full last name, enter the first few characters to return all records starting with that string. For example 'Smi' will return properties which include the owner last names 'Smith' and 'Smithson', etc. This is a required field.

    Type a full or partial first name into the field. If you do not know the full first name, enter the first few characters to return all records starting with that string. For example 'Jo' will return properties which include the owner first names 'John' and 'Joanne', etc.

    Type a suburb into the field. For example: "Epping".

      Search

      Type a full or partial Volume Number into the field. if you do not know the full Volume number, enter the first few numbers to return all records starting with that volume number. For example '123' will return properties which include the Volume/Folio '123/123' and "1234/123', etc. This is a required field.

      Type a full or partial folio number into the field.             There are 2 ways to refine by radius, by using the dropdown:

            • Refine by distance (km): locates the properties within the specified distance from the target property. This is most useful in urban areas where a large number of properties are located a small distance from the target.
            • Refine by number of properties: locates the nearest number of properties from the target property. This is most useful in rural areas where neighbouring properties may be a large distance away.

            The 'Target suburb only' shows the closest properties only within the suburb of the Target property.

            Switching between the additional tabs (E.g. Sales History, On the Market) will further refine the 'Property' tab results to show a subset of properties. For example, selecting 50 properties from the Radius dropdown will result in 50 properties on the Property tab, but will return a smaller subset of properties on the remaining tabs (Sales History, On the Market etc).

                              Rental Status

                              The Rental Status has been derived using the following logic: Likely Rental:
                              • Last Rental Date is 0-24 months ago and no Sale
                              Maybe Rental:
                              • Last Rental Date is more than 24 months and no Sale
                              • Last Rental Date is more than 24 months and Sale within 6 months of the Last Rental Date
                              • Last Rental Date is 0-24 months ago and Sale 18-24 months ago
                              Unlikely Rental:
                              • No Rental Date
                              • Last Rental Date is more than 24months and Sale more than 6 months after the last Rental Date
                              • Last Rental Date is 0-24 months ago and Sale within last 18 months

                                                      Property Types

                                                      Properties have been defined according to the following broad definitions:
                                                      • House: Any freestanding residential property
                                                      • Unit: A residential strata titled unit in a building with no lift
                                                      • Highrise: A residential strata titled unit in a building with a lift
                                                      • Industrial Suite: A strata titled industrial unit within a complex of many industrial units
                                                      • Complete Offic Block: A wholly owned freestanding commercial building on one title
                                                      • Commercial Suite: A strata titled office within a commercial complex of many suites
                                                      • Industrial Building: A wholly owned freestanding industrial building on one title

                                                      In this field we need to know the year of construction commencement for your property. If you don't know this answer the relevant local council may be of assistance to you.

                                                      Years

                                                      What does Years represent?

                                                      Each year represents a full financial year. This calculator provides an estimate of the likely allowances on the basis your are going to settle on the property today.For example, Year 1 represents the amount you can claim over the next 365 days if you purchased a similar property to data you have already entered in.                                                                                                             		Diminishing Value

                                                      What does the Diminishing Value and Prime Cost method mean?

                                                      Both terms refer to the way in which plant and equipment is depreciated in accordance with the ATO guidelines.The Diminishing Value method accelerates the allowances in the earlier years, where as the Prime Cost method evenly spreads the allowance out.                                                                                                             		Prime Cost

                                                      What does the Diminishing Value and Prime Cost method mean?

                                                      Both terms refer to the way in which plant and equipment is depreciated in accordance with the ATO guidelines.The Diminishing Value method accelerates the allowances in the earlier years, where as the Prime Cost method evenly spreads the allowance out.
                                                      Degree of Accuracy:

                                                      How does the Degree of Accuracy work?

                                                      The higher the rating, the greater the degree of accuracy!For instance if your property receives a Low rating, it means the Calculator has only been able to find a limited amount of properties that match your criteria.However, if you receive a High rating, the Tax Depreciation Calculator has been able to find a wide range of similar properties. This increases the rate of accuracy.We must stress there is no 100% guarantee.

                                                      Derived List Price

                                                      First Advertised $ and Last Advertised $ - represents the first listing price RP Data recorded in the advertising campaign for the property. In some instances we may have to derive a price from the advertisement. In those instances we apply the following logic:

                                                      • The value may represent the numerical component of a description e.g. Offers Over $550,000 would be displayed as $550,000.
                                                      • If a range of values is provided, we may take the midpoint e.g. Offers between $600,000 - $650,000 would be displayed as $625,000.
                                                      • When the listing type is Auction or Tender we display the word e.g. "Auction" or "Tender".

                                                      % First $ to Last Ad $ - represents the % change between the displayed First Advertised $ and the displayed Last Advertised $. Where the displayed First Advertised $ or the displayed Last Advertised $'s list type is Auction or Tender, no calculation is performed.

                                                      % Last $ to Actual Sale - represents the % change between the displayed Last Advertised $ and the Actual Sale Price recorded by RP Data. Where the displayed Last Advertised $'s list type is Auction or Tender, no calculation is performed.

                                                      % Total Change - represents the % change between the displayed First Advertised $ and the Actual Sale Price recorded by RP Data. Where the displayed First Advertised $'s list type is Auction or Tender, no calculation is performed.

                                                      Marketing Extract

                                                      RP Data's customers can confidently use the Marketing Database for marketing purposes with an average of 3600 properties per postcode with at least 1 contact. This consumer contact data (that is names and phone numbers associated with a residential address) is subject to a warranty to be compliant with Australia's National Privacy Principles. The data is sourced from a range of sources including telephone directory listings, historical electoral roles and subscriptions to magazines and special interest groups.

                                                      The number of records available from the Marketing Database for export vary by area. You can see how many are available by clicking on the Direct Marketing tab after doing a postcode or suburb search. The number of properties covered is the number displayed on the tab in brackets. The data is constantly updated to maintain compliance and users should only extract what they need per day.

                                                      • Phone Listings: There is still an obligation on the end user, the subscriber, to check if any phone numbers that are extracted have been placed on the DNC list just prior to making any outbound sales and marketing calls.
                                                      • Head of Household: This is generally a modelled attribute based on either a survey response or an assumption, i.e. the only occupant of a one person household. As such it is an indicative attribute only.
                                                      • Gender: This is generally a modelled attribute based on either the source of data or, more often, an analysis of the Christian names of the person. Hence 'Robert' is deemed a male and 'Lesley' a female.
